<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF8AFFC0A7ADF8FEFE29DBE9" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF8AFFC0A7ADF8FEFEB8DB2A" blockId="19.[189,382,1809,1835]" box="[189,382,1809,1835]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF8AFFC0A7ADF8FEFEB8DB2A" bold="true" box="[189,382,1809,1835]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF8AFFC0A7ADF8FEFEB8DB2A" bold="true" box="[189,382,1809,1835]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Natural history</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF8AFFC0A7ADF8AFFE29DBE9" blockId="19.[187,1399,1856,2024]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Inhabits decomposing parts of fallen tree logs and deserted termite galleries in broadleaf forest; collected with 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF8AFFC0A7EBF88CFD55DB7F" authority="Francke, 1977" authorityName="Francke" authorityYear="1977" box="[251,659,1891,1918]" class="Arachnida" family="Diplocentridae" genus="Diplocentrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maya">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF8AFFC0A7EBF88CFE18DB7C" box="[251,478,1891,1917]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diplocentrus maya</emphasis>
Francke, 1977
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF8AFFC0A5B4F88CFCEBDB7C" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1810" box="[676,813,1891,1917]" class="Arachnida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Scorpiones</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF8AFFC0A42AF88CFB55DB7F" authority="Karsch, 1880" authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1880" box="[826,1171,1891,1918]" class="Arachnida" family="Diplocentridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Diplocentridae Karsch, 1880</taxonomicName>
) and millipedes of the order 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF8AFFC0A624F868FDADDBA3" authority="Cook, 1895" authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1895" box="[308,619,1927,1954]" order="Platydesmida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="order">Platydesmida Cook, 1895</taxonomicName>
. More than one individual was collected in the same log cavity, suggesting a degree of tolerance towards conspecifics. The species was observed to prey on small insects and spiders inside the log.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
